Title: Galileo's Middle Finger: Heretics, Activists, and the Search for Justice in Science
Author: Alice Domurat Dreger
My Review: I didn't mind that the book end up having nothing about Galileo except his middle finger, which, don't get me wrong, was a nice story. However, it was bad for different reasons, there was too much namesdropping and citing of other reaserches which we're irelevent provided they did not lead to anything more than limited conclusions. The fluff was also too much for me. I am interested to know more about sexual anomalies and how they are perceived, referred to, etc. but not about how an academic felt after writing a book about the people who were born with them.

Title: The Miserable Mill (A Series of Unfortunate Events, #4)
Author: Lemony Snicket
My Review:
I read the first three books in the series nearly 10 years ago and I still think the series is pretty amazing. It has all a child'd enjoy - a protagonist and an antagonist, a misfortune and an adventure, and a resolution at the end. Not a happy end, tho. One should crave more of the adventures in the books to come and wait for the happy end for the Baudelaire children.
Now that I've read the book and not being a 10-year-old, I can see the huge amount of references and the choice of the names of all characters, which I haven't seen before.
This book was a nostalgic reminiscence for me of what kind of books I read when I was little and why I read them, sympathizing with the boy who loved more than anything to read and joining the three protagonists in their adventures.

Title: Odd and the Frost Giants
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review: Neil Gaiman is an amazing storyteller. It doesn't matter what kind of book you are looking for, whichever of his book you take, you won’t be disappointed. This book is a perfect little getaway into a magical world on a cold Saturday afternoon.

Title: Nederlands Voor Buitenlanders (Delftse Methode)
Author: F. Montens
My Review: I didn't like it. There were no explanations of the grammar and it was really hard to figure out what the "lesson" was exactly. The exercises were too repetitive. The only good thing was that the units were short and there was no information overload.

Title: Mightier Than The Sword: How The News Media Have Shaped American History
Author: Rodger Streitmatter

Title: The Pirate's Dilemma: How Youth Culture Is Reinventing Capitalism
Author: Matt Mason
My Review:
I found the book to be a fun read and occasionally engaging but definitely nothing serious or a source for basing your arguments on. It was interesting to learn the author's viewpoint on youth subcultures but, at the time reading those opinions, I thought how idealistic they were. When I read the book, I felt like the author was trying to find a good argument why subcultures were a good thing and to bring the debate on subcultures on a more sophisticated level - definitely an ambitious thing to do. They are good because they bring innovation with them as almost everything else actually.
Nevertheless, I definitely learned some interesting things from the essays in the book and will recommend it to someone who is looking for an easy-paced read.

Title: Issues in Internet Law: Society, Technology, and the Law
Author: Keith B. Darrell

Title: A Spy in the House of Love
Author: Anaïs Nin
My Review:
The “Multitudes of Sabina” or A Spy in the House of Love is a novel about keeping yourself alive, while reinventing love, venturing in affair after another, hoping you won’t hurt the other person and knowing at the same time that you will. It is as if no one knows Sabina’s real name and her real self, neither does she, and no one is able to possess her. This is not a novel about love, but a novel about guilt and redemption, fear of the mundane and paranoia.
I am not exactly sure whether or not I like the book, but it definitely struck me as an honest piece. I didn't like the premise of a mischievous woman cheating constantly on her husband and lovers. Nevertheless, the leitmotiv of trying to find yourself, to reinvent yourself and to make peace with yourself is what I liked the most about the novel. Although there is a protagonist, Sabina, the author’s voice echoes through the pages. The writing is so fluid and it grabs your attention, so you can’t stop reading. The lack of separation in chapters makes you read incessantly.
